✅ 3. CLI Reference Manual

Assuming your CLI entry point is saab:

`
saab
├── can
│   ├── open
│   ├── send
│   ├── recv
│   └── test
├── uds
│   ├── read-did
│   ├── session
│   └── dtc
├── tech2
│   ├── start
│   ├── dtc
│   └── info
├── sps
│   ├── prepare
│   ├── flash
│   └── verify
└── replay
    ├── play
    └── list
`

Example: saab can test

`
saab can test
    Opens the CAN interface, sends a test frame, waits for a response.
`

Example: saab uds read-did 0xF190

`
Reads VIN from the target ECU.
`

---

✅ 4. Developer Onboarding Guide

🧭 Architecture Overview

SAAB Suite uses a ports & adapters (hexagonal) architecture:

- ports/ — abstract interfaces  
- adapters/ — concrete implementations  
- domain/ — pure business logic  
- kernel/ — shared types  
- runtime/ — configuration + environment  

This keeps hardware, protocols, and UI layers isolated.

---

🛠️ Development Setup

`
git clone ~/saab-suite
cd ~/saab-suite
python3 -m venv .venv
. .venv/bin/activate
pip install -e .
pip install pytest ruff mypy
`

---

🧪 Running Tests

`
pytest -q
`

---

🧹 Linting

`
ruff check .
mypy src/
`

---

🧩 Adding a New Adapter

1. Create a class in adapters/<type>/
2. Implement the corresponding interface in ports/
3. Add configuration keys in runtime/
4. Add tests in tests/adapters/

---

🔌 Adding a New UDS Service

1. Add a method in diag/uds/services.py
2. Add a wrapper in diag/uds/client.py
3. Add tests
4. Document it in docs/diagnostics.md

---
